Implementation Plan - AI Data Team Command Matrix & Specialized Agent Chat
This plan details the end-to-end specifications to consolidate the separate "chat vs pipeline" pages into a single, unified Universal AI Data Team Workspace. The workflow stages are represented as 6 specialized AI agents (E, D, S, R, T, X) overseen by the universal supervisor Agent Dhara. The chat drawer will dynamically adapt to the active agent, supporting natural to-and-fro conversations, background agent-to-agent coordination, and human-in-the-loop approvals before handing off tasks to the next expert.
User Review Required
IMPORTANT
Agentic Collaboration & Background Coordination
Coordination: When you are working with the Extraction Specialist (E) and ask to check quality, E doesn't just say "no". E coordinates with the Data Quality Auditor (D), runs the data quality assessment in the background, reports a summary of the findings (e.g., "I have run the quality audit. We found 3 high-severity issues. Let me transition you to Bianca, our Data Quality Auditor..."), and then hands you off.
Human-in-the-Loop Approvals: When an agent finishes their task (e.g., Agent S infers semantics, Agent T generates ETL code), they will present the result in the chat and ask for your approval (e.g., "Does this generated code look correct? Please approve so I can hand this over to Thomas, our Deployment Executor (X)...").
To-and-Fro Conversations: The chat is fully interactive. If you ask Agent D to modify a quality rule or tell Agent S to change a column classification (e.g., "Change customer_id from email to numeric"), the agent performs the modification, updates the workspace context, and shows you the updated result in the chat.
IMPORTANT
AI Data Team Command Matrix (6 Specialized Agents) Rather than a simple vertical stepper, we will design a futuristic Control Hub Cluster containing 6 Agent cards with stylized letter monograms and proper titles:
Extraction Specialist (E): Connects to sources (Azure SQL, Blob, Filesystem) and extracts raw data.
Data Quality Auditor (D): Runs data profiling, audits quality anomalies, and validates the Great Expectations DQ Gate.
Semantic Specialist (S): Auto-infers column datatypes (e.g. Email, Phone, Address) using LLM enrichment.
Requirements Specialist (R): Translates natural language requirements into structured rules.
Transformation Engineer (T): Auto-generates clean, optimized T-SQL or Python/Pandas ETL script code.
Deployment Executor (X): Performs dry runs, deploys statements directly on Azure SQL, and mirrors to Fabric Lakehouse.
Roadmap & Future Extensions: Azure Blob & MS Fabric Pipeline
To future-proof the architecture for Azure Blob Storage and Microsoft Fabric, we will layout the expansion path for the 6 agents to support file-based lakehouse ingestion and PySpark processing:
[Azure Blob Storage (Raw Files)]             │             │ (Agent E: Fabric Shortcut / Data Pipeline Copy)             ▼[Fabric OneLake Files (Raw Zone)]             │             │ (Agent T: Generates PySpark ETL Code)             ▼[Fabric Spark Notebook Executing PySpark]             │             │ (Agent X: Triggers Spark Execution)             ▼[Fabric Lakehouse Tables (Cleaned Delta Tables)]             │             ▼[Power BI & Downstream Consumers]
Agent-Specific Roles in Blob/Fabric Ingestion:
Extraction Specialist (E):
Identifies and classifies files into three categories:
Native ETL-ready (Phase 1): CSV, TSV/PSV/delimited text, JSON/JSONL, Parquet.
Supported with Extra Handling: Excel, XML, Avro, ORC.
Excluded (Non-ETL): PDF, DOCX, PPTX, Images, Audio, Video, Binaries (flagged as unstructured parsing problems, not data cleaning candidates).
automates linking files to Fabric OneLake Files (Raw Zone) using Shortcuts or Data Pipeline copies.
Data Quality Auditor (D):
Profiles file datasets and runs custom quality audits directly on pandas/parquet metadata snapshots.
Transformation Engineer (T):
Generates optimized PySpark transformation code to clean raw files and format them for Delta lake ingestion.
Deployment Executor (X):
Triggers the execution of Fabric Spark Notebooks hosting the PySpark scripts to output clean Delta tables in Fabric Lakehouse Tables (Cleaned Zone).
